40|$|The potted {{chrysanthemum}} {{is one of}} {{the main}} flowers produced in protected cultivation. Silicon has promoted improvements both in quantitative and qualitative aspects when supplied to some ornamental species produced in these conditions. We evaluated the response of chrysanthemum cultivars grown in pots to the application of silicon. The experiment was conducted in a greenhouse of the Universidade Federal de Viçosa, Minas Gerais state, Brazil. Treatments were arranged in a 3 x 2 factorial scheme (three cultivars of chrysanthemum: Coral Charm, <b>White</b> <b>Reagan</b> and Indianapolis and two doses of silicon: 0 and 800 mg kg- 1) with six replications, in an entirely randomized design. We evaluated the diameter of the flower buds and stems; length of the flower stems; height of the plants; dry matter production of roots, leaves, stems, inflorescence and shoots; total number of inflorescences; diameter of the most fully open inflorescences; Si content in the leaf tissue; and flowering cycle and shelf life. <b>The</b> <b>White</b> <b>Reagan</b> cultivar produced <b>the</b> greatest number of inflorescences (29. 17) per pot and proved to be more precocious (85. 83 days). There was no negative interaction between Si, Ca and K and no effect of silicon was shown on the production and shelf life of the chrysanthemum. There was an increase in the content of this element in the leaves with the application of potassium metasilicate...|$|R
